00:14:42.016 --> 00:14:43.640
didn't know when he
was younger that he

00:14:43.640 --> 00:14:45.910
was working on a computer.

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:47.900
They just saw him
on the computer.

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:51.060
So what he would do, and what's
very important for you to do,

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:54.180
is make it clear that you are
using these screens-- when

00:14:54.180 --> 00:14:57.060
you're using them for work--
make it clear that it's

00:14:57.060 --> 00:15:00.145
a tool, that you are using it
for whatever you need to do.

00:15:00.145 --> 00:15:01.520
And it could just
be hanging out.

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:03.080
It could be talking to Grandma.

00:15:03.080 --> 00:15:05.240
It could be any other
thing like that,

00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:09.910
but it's not just something that
you're just spacing out with,

00:15:09.910 --> 00:15:13.380
or spending tons of
time googling things,

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:15.000
or things like that.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.194
And content choices,
like we said,

00:15:17.194 --> 00:15:18.860
show children how to
tell the difference

00:15:18.860 --> 00:15:21.480
between the good stuff
and the bad stuff.

00:15:21.480 --> 00:15:23.770
So that's my second takeaway.

00:15:23.770 --> 00:15:25.440
Content matters.

00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:28.300
You'll see that
in the AAP thing.

00:15:28.300 --> 00:15:29.800
And I'm gonna tell
you about a study

00:15:29.800 --> 00:15:34.490
that I did at UCLA while I
was getting my dissertation,

00:15:34.490 --> 00:15:37.570
where I looked at values
in television content.

00:15:37.570 --> 00:15:40.790
So I looked at changing
values in television content.

00:15:40.790 --> 00:15:43.430
And I looked at
television shows from '67

00:15:43.430 --> 00:15:47.000
all the way up to 2007,
and asked people what

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:48.220
they thought the values were.

00:15:48.220 --> 00:15:50.724
So we all know that you have
to pay attention to sex.

00:15:50.724 --> 00:15:52.640
We know you have to pay
attention to violence.

00:15:52.640 --> 00:15:53.810
We know you have
to pay attention

00:15:53.810 --> 00:15:54.950
to all these other things.

00:15:54.950 --> 00:15:56.324
You may not always
think you even

00:15:56.324 --> 00:16:00.930
have to pay attention to
values, but values come across,

00:16:00.930 --> 00:16:02.630
and they change.

00:16:02.630 --> 00:16:05.680
Does anyone wanna guess what
the value was in the top shows?

00:16:08.580 --> 00:16:11.910
In the top shows, it with
family, community feeling.

00:16:11.910 --> 00:16:13.690
In the bottom, it was fame.

00:16:13.690 --> 00:16:16.400
And what ended up happening
was in the top shows,

00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:17.750
fame was at the bottom.

00:16:17.750 --> 00:16:21.430
It was the number 16th value
in the television shows.

00:16:21.430 --> 00:16:23.690
Out of 16 values, it
was at the bottom.

00:16:23.690 --> 00:16:27.910
And in 2007, when "Hannah
Montana" came out,

00:16:27.910 --> 00:16:31.210
and other shows, like "The
Kardashians," reality TV,

00:16:31.210 --> 00:16:32.550
it was the number one value.

00:16:32.550 --> 00:16:33.340
So it flipped.

00:16:33.340 --> 00:16:35.020
So it was really bizarre.

00:16:35.020 --> 00:16:38.210
And what we found as we
continued to look at it

00:16:38.210 --> 00:16:41.840
is that this was just a
small study in Los Angeles.

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:45.150
And we found that the kids were
picking up on the messages.

00:16:45.150 --> 00:16:49.030
So I asked them
about these TV shows.

00:16:49.030 --> 00:16:51.990
And then it turned out they
were using social media,

00:16:51.990 --> 00:16:55.520
and actually understood
that they could get

00:16:55.520 --> 00:16:57.210
an audience with social media.

00:16:57.210 --> 00:17:00.024
So at fourth and fifth
grade-- I did focus groups

00:17:00.024 --> 00:17:01.190
of fourth and fifth graders.

00:17:01.190 --> 00:17:02.680
They were picking up
on these messages.

00:17:02.680 --> 00:17:05.109
So there are all sorts of
messages they're picking up on,

00:17:05.109 --> 00:17:09.000
and it's really important for
you to pay attention to it.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.740
So as I said, here's the
American Academy of Pediatrics.

00:17:12.740 --> 00:17:16.050
This is just a small part of
what they put in this article.

00:17:16.050 --> 00:17:17.099
Content matters.

00:17:17.099 --> 00:17:18.910
The quality of the
content is more

00:17:18.910 --> 00:17:21.819
important than the platform
or time spent with media.

00:17:21.819 --> 00:17:23.780
They took all the research.

00:17:23.780 --> 00:17:25.040
Some of it's in my book.

00:17:25.040 --> 00:17:26.136
A lot more isn't.

00:17:26.136 --> 00:17:27.510
They took it all,
and they talked

00:17:27.510 --> 00:17:30.900
to a whole bunch of
researchers, and they came up

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:32.930
with these recommendations.

00:17:32.930 --> 00:17:34.830
And curation helps.

00:17:34.830 --> 00:17:37.190
There's another great book
called "Click, Tap, Read"

00:17:37.190 --> 00:17:40.250
that came out about apps,
and it talks about this.

00:17:40.250 --> 00:17:43.690
80,000 apps are
labeled as educational,

00:17:43.690 --> 00:17:45.910
but they're labeled
educational by the developer.

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:48.580
There's no real research,
usually, proving

00:17:48.580 --> 00:17:49.890
that they're educational.

00:17:49.890 --> 00:17:53.630
So it's important to pay
attention to them if you can.

