00:21:56.190 --> 00:21:59.930
So bottom line, curate
and check the ratings

00:21:59.930 --> 00:22:02.130
from an independent
source, if possible.

00:22:02.130 --> 00:22:04.440
And teach your child how
to do it for themselves,

00:22:04.440 --> 00:22:05.810
just like Brad said.

00:22:05.810 --> 00:22:09.320
When you teach your child
to do it for themselves,

00:22:09.320 --> 00:22:12.220
they start to learn to think
critically about this stuff

00:22:12.220 --> 00:22:14.960
themselves, and make
their own judgment,

00:22:14.960 --> 00:22:17.720
and learn what they like
and they don't like.

00:22:17.720 --> 00:22:20.410
Co-viewing the content even
a few minutes with them

00:22:20.410 --> 00:22:21.570
will help.

00:22:21.570 --> 00:22:24.360
Converse, use the
messages in the content

00:22:24.360 --> 00:22:26.770
to draw out your family
values and talk about it.

00:22:26.770 --> 00:22:29.100
Every family is different.

00:22:29.100 --> 00:22:34.200
I like to say, in
France, people in France

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:38.330
are not as worried
about sexual content,

00:22:38.330 --> 00:22:40.930
but they may be worried,
more worried, about violence.

00:22:40.930 --> 00:22:42.270
It's different here.

00:22:42.270 --> 00:22:45.920
So it's really important for
you to know what you care about

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:47.480
and what your
family cares about,

00:22:47.480 --> 00:22:50.660
and use what's in the
content to draw your

00:22:50.660 --> 00:22:53.570
out your family values.

00:22:53.570 --> 00:22:57.710
So number three, prioritize
face-to-face time.

00:22:57.710 --> 00:22:59.790
So no one wants
to be this family,

00:22:59.790 --> 00:23:02.500
I hope, in "Modern Family,"
although some of us

00:23:02.500 --> 00:23:06.020
are this family more
than we care to admit.

00:23:06.020 --> 00:23:09.570
And this really came
home to roost for me.

00:23:09.570 --> 00:23:13.140
I mean, I've always known
it, but I did a study.

00:23:13.140 --> 00:23:16.330
It was in the press quite a bit.

00:23:16.330 --> 00:23:20.070
So some of you may know it.

00:23:20.070 --> 00:23:22.540
I was really
worried, because you

00:23:22.540 --> 00:23:26.200
saw that picture of all those
girls staring at these screens?

00:23:26.200 --> 00:23:28.950
I was scared they were
staring at this, instead

00:23:28.950 --> 00:23:30.080
of staring face-to-face.

00:23:30.080 --> 00:23:32.660
So I wanted to design
a study to look at it.

00:23:32.660 --> 00:23:38.270
So this study, we
looked at kids,

00:23:38.270 --> 00:23:41.840
and we compared, two sets
of kids, control group

00:23:41.840 --> 00:23:42.960
and experimental.

00:23:42.960 --> 00:23:45.080
The ones on the left--
these aren't the real kids.

00:23:45.080 --> 00:23:49.540
I just found these pictures--
were going to school as usual.

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:51.370
They had media out of school.

00:23:51.370 --> 00:23:54.740
They spent 4 and 1/2
hours a day out of school.

00:23:54.740 --> 00:23:56.080
That was their average.

00:23:56.080 --> 00:24:00.450
They reported it,
self-report, using media.

00:24:00.450 --> 00:24:03.540
That's lower than the
national average, by the way.

00:24:03.540 --> 00:24:07.540
And the other kids went to this
camp, outdoor education camp.

00:24:07.540 --> 00:24:11.340
And they had no media,
no screens for five days.

00:24:11.340 --> 00:24:14.290
And what we did
is we tested them

00:24:14.290 --> 00:24:17.710
on their ability to understand
non-verbal communications

00:24:17.710 --> 00:24:19.040
skills.

00:24:19.040 --> 00:24:21.080
So we did a pre and a post.

00:24:21.080 --> 00:24:23.560
So we did a test
before and after,

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:26.420
right when they got to the
camp, on the Monday first thing

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:30.180
at school, end of the day
Friday when they left the camp.

00:24:30.180 --> 00:24:32.280
And we asked them
to write down what

00:24:32.280 --> 00:24:35.724
emotions photos of faces,
which were adults and children,

00:24:35.724 --> 00:24:37.390
and they had four
different expressions.

00:24:37.390 --> 00:24:39.690
And we asked them to tell us
what the expressions were.

00:24:39.690 --> 00:24:41.500
And we did it pre and post.

00:24:41.500 --> 00:24:44.440
And we also showed videos, and
these videos were very much

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:45.800
like Charlie Brown videos.

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:49.630
The tone was taken out, so
they were like-- but I mean,

00:24:49.630 --> 00:24:51.970
the tone was there, but the
verbal content was removed.

00:24:51.970 --> 00:24:55.660
So you could hear somebody
sounding like they

00:24:55.660 --> 00:24:57.860
were happy or unhappy.

00:24:57.860 --> 00:25:01.095
This was a girl who got
a really ugly sweater.

00:25:01.095 --> 00:25:02.950
At first, she was
very excited she was

00:25:02.950 --> 00:25:04.750
gonna get a sweater, a present.

00:25:04.750 --> 00:25:05.800
And she was like, yeah!

00:25:05.800 --> 00:25:07.220
And then she got that.

00:25:07.220 --> 00:25:09.580
So there were
transitions in emotions.

00:25:09.580 --> 00:25:11.370
So these were the two tests.

00:25:11.370 --> 00:25:13.990
And what we found
is within five days,

00:25:13.990 --> 00:25:16.150
the kids who went
to the camp improved

00:25:16.150 --> 00:25:19.750
in both measures over the
kids who used the media.

00:25:19.750 --> 00:25:21.770
In other words, they
better understood

00:25:21.770 --> 00:25:24.210
nonverbal emotional cues.

00:25:24.210 --> 00:25:25.170
So what does that mean?

00:25:25.170 --> 00:25:29.030
We didn't think that meant that
the screens were taking away

00:25:29.030 --> 00:25:32.510
their ability to
read emotional cues.

00:25:32.510 --> 00:25:34.840
We felt that the
reason that they

00:25:34.840 --> 00:25:38.620
were able to do that was
because-- this was the New York

00:25:38.620 --> 00:25:41.090
Times title, that one they
wrote about it, which I thought

00:25:41.090 --> 00:25:43.640
was pretty funny.

00:25:43.640 --> 00:25:46.180
It was that they were
staring at people's faces.

00:25:46.180 --> 00:25:48.460
Even in sixth grade, these
were sixth grade kids,

00:25:48.460 --> 00:25:50.880
they were still
learning emotional cues,

00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:53.470
because they spent a whole
week looking at people's faces.

00:25:53.470 --> 00:25:56.100
So it's really important
to make sure you

00:25:56.100 --> 00:25:59.360
build face-to-face
time into your life,

00:25:59.360 --> 00:26:02.680
into your children's lives,
and into your own lives.

00:26:02.680 --> 00:26:05.960
So on the bottom line, kids
need to practice to learn

00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:08.260
social and emotional skills.

00:26:08.260 --> 00:26:11.300
You should build face-to-face
time into each day.

00:26:11.300 --> 00:26:14.340
Hopefully you do, but especially
when they're really young,

00:26:14.340 --> 00:26:17.560
you may not be thinking about
this, but as they get older,

00:26:17.560 --> 00:26:19.160
it'll be harder and harder.

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:22.340
Find spaces in your
house without screens.

00:26:22.340 --> 00:26:25.320
Take longer breaks if
you can sometimes, like

00:26:25.320 --> 00:26:26.410
a couple of days.

00:26:26.410 --> 00:26:29.840
Go camping as long as you can.

00:26:29.840 --> 00:26:33.560
And of course, watch
your own behavior.

00:26:33.560 --> 00:26:37.240
And lastly, stay positive.

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:39.660
So this is a quote
by Howard Gardner.

00:26:39.660 --> 00:26:42.120
He's the guy that wrote
"Multiple Intelligences."

